Module kivakit.core
Package com.telenav.kivakit.core.path

Class StringPath

java.lang.Object
com.telenav.kivakit.core.path.Path<String>
com.telenav.kivakit.core.path.StringPath
All Implemented Interfaces:
Emptiness, Sized, AsString, StringFormattable, Comparable<Path<String>>, Iterable<String>
Direct Known Subclasses:
PackageReference, ResourcePath
public class StringPath extends Path<String>
A Path of strings that has a given separator string. This class contains numerous methods which down-cast the return value of the superclass to make use easier for clients. Methods that are unique to this class mainly have to do with the conversion of StringPaths to and from string * values:

String Values

  • asContraction(int) - This path as a contracted string of the given maximum length
  • asJavaPath() - This path as a Path
  • asString() - This path as a string
  • endsWith(String) - True if this path ends with the given suffix when joined
  • join() - This path joined by the path separator()
  • join(String) - This path joined with the given separator
  • separator() - The separator string for this path, by default this is a forward slash
  • startsWith(String) - True if this path starts with the given prefix when joined
  • withSeparator(String) - This path with the given separator string

Parsing

  • parseStringPath(Listener listener, String, String) - A string path for the given string and separator
  • parseStringPath(Listener listener, String, String, String) - A string for the given root pattern, string and separator

Factories

  • stringPath(URI) - A string path for the given URI
  • - A string path for the given list of elements
  • stringPath(java.nio.file.Path) - A string path for the given Java NIO path

      public StringPath subpath(int start, int end)
      Returns the sub-path of this path starting at given start index (inclusive) and extending to the end index (exclusive). If start and end are equal, the empty path is returned. If start and end are not equal and the path is absolute, the sub-path will still be absolute with the same root. If the start and end indexes are invalid, null is returned.
